As per the decree of the Supreme Council of the Supreme Council of the RSFSR, in the spring of 1953, classes are begun at the Yeysk school team for a full-scale staffing of the crews of the ships of the Azov and Black Seas Fleet. The school trained flight engineers, navigators, mechanics, radio operators, telegraph operators and refrigeration setters. The annual increase in the number of cadets served in October 1961 as the reason for the renaming of the institution in accordance with the resolution of the Council of Ministers of the RSFSR in the Yeysk Fishery Technical College.

In accordance with the decision of the Ministry of Sea Fleet of the USSR in June 1963, the control over the institution was transferred to the Main Directorate of the Fishing Industry, and the composition of specialities was expanded by the profession of a mechanic for equipping the fishing fleet vessels. In early 1968, the institution was reorganized into the Yeysk Marine Fisheries Technical School, moved in 1974 to the educational and administrative building, consisting of the assembly and sports halls, the bibliographic department, lecture rooms, and repair and mechanical workshops.

Owing to the continuous search for effective methods of teaching, the pedagogical team successfully coped with the consequences of the nineties, and in 2012 the institution becomes a branch of the Astrakhan State Technical University, which does not stop providing the personnel of the crews of the floating bases of the Krasnodar Krai.

Currently the educational institution awards the following degrees:
• Certificate of Secondary Vocational Education (“Diplom o srednem specialnom obrazovanii”).

