The purposes for which the Trust is established are to receive, hold, manage and administer the Trust Fund for every charitable purpose benefiting Ngāti Tūwharetoa including:

(a) the protection and enhancement of the mana and rangatiratanga of Ngāti Tūwharetoa, its taonga, its Arikitanga and its members;

(b) the promotion of the educational, spiritual, economic, social and cultural advancement and well-being of Ngāti Tūwharetoa and its Hapū;

(c) the maintenance and establishment of places of cultural or spiritual significance to Ngāti Tūwharetoa;

(d) the promotion within Ngāti Tūwharetoa of health and well-being and relief of the aged; and
(e) any other matter beneficial to the community of Ngāti Tūwharetoa and all the Members of Ngāti Tūwharetoa.

Onze werkzaamheden betreffen het wekelijks lossen van de vissersschepen. Hieronder verstaan wij:
- Lossen van de vis;
- Schoonmaken van het visruim;
- Terugladen van lege kisten voor de volgende vistrip;

Deze werkzaamheden worden uitgevoerd door ervaren teams met oog voor kwaliteit. 

De voornaamste haven waar de loswerkzaamheden worden uitgevoerd is Harlingen. Ook zijn wij  bereid uit te wijken naar andere havens in Nederland, zoals Eemshaven, IJmuiden en Delfzijl.

Americas Gleaned Seafood (AGS) is committed to:

          1.  Reduce hunger by connecting the fishing industry to food banks so seafood left after the harvest can be gleaned to feed food-insecure people;

          2.  Coordinate the gleaning program with regulatory and non-governmental organizations involved in collecting, processing and distributing food resources;

          3.  Educate the public on how seafood gleaning can reduce hunger and nutrition-related health issues amongst low-income families;

          4.  Provide data to oversight agencies and organizations for improved fishery management.


AGS recruits fishing co-ops, docks and commercial fishermen. Each port maintains seafood gleaning boxes where fishermen deposit their bycatch donations. Seafood processing partners pick up and process the gleaned seafood to be labeled and delivered to partnering food banks. Along with simple, corresponding recipes, the gleaned seafood is distributed to families in need through foodbanks, soup kitchens and shelters among other programs.

With as little as a $50 donation, eighty 4 oz. portions of locally, sustainably caught seafood can help feed hungry families.

Low-income families, who do not have the resources to afford high-quality protein like seafood, get the food they need to live and be healthy. Foodbanks receive items that are only rarely available or affordable. NJ’s commercial fishing industry is supported and promoted as a partner in reducing the amount of unused seafood and helping to feed local families. Additionally, the program provides important data for better fishery management and environmental sustainability.
